<h2 id="summary">Summary:</h2>
<p>In papyri, the dominant order of the major constituents in the
sentence varies according to the text type. Verbal-initial patterns are
strongly represented in private and legal texts, while petitions are
abundant with Subject-initial order patterns.</p>
<h2 id="examples-from-papygreek-corpus">Example(s) from PapyGreek
corpus:</h2>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion:</h2>
<h3 id="classical-greek">Classical Greek</h3>
<p>The leading explanation for the order patterns of the major sentence
constituents is that it is pragmatically determined and fixed. The basic
pattern suggested by Helma Dik (<span class="citation" data-cites="dik1995">(Dik 1995)</span>, <span class="citation" data-cites="dik2007">(Dik 2007)</span>) is the following:</p>
<p><em>(Setting) - Topic - Focus - Verb - Remainder</em></p>
<p>Within this framework, permutations and variations are possible, in
order to link individual utterances in the discourse and contrast them
against, or present as a continuation of, a previously stated idea <span class="citation" data-cites="celano2014">(Celano 2014a)</span>.</p>
<p>However, since the AGDT treebanking framework utilised for the
annotation of our corpus and the other major treebanked corpora used as
reference points in this discussion does not record information about
pragmatic function, it is impossible to test how pragmatics influences
the ordering of the constituents in them through programmatic means.</p>
<h3 id="shift-in-koine-towards-vso">Shift in Koine towards VSO</h3>
<p><span class="citation" data-cites="horrocks2007">Horrocks
(2007)</span> discusses the establishment of VSO and SVO patterns as
most frequent ordering of the major sentence constituents in Koine, in
contrast to the predominant verb-final structures in Classical Greek,
and proposes an explanation for this shift based on the role of clitics.
In verb-final sentences, it is possible for clitics, due to their
tendency to cluster in second position, to sometimes occur too far away
from the verb that governs them, putting a strain on the attention of
the reader/listener. A possible solution to this “problem” can be
achieved by displacing the clitic from its second position and moving it
directly after the verbal head. In the Hellenistic period, a
“compromise” between these two options starts to appear in the form of
the pattern <em>Verb + clitic + Subject + Object</em>. By admitting the
verb first, the clitics can occupy their prefered second place and still
be close enough to their governor. With time this ordering became
preferred even in utterances without a clitic whose place needed to be
negotiated. As for the SVO pattern, it most likely naturally occurred
from the preposing of the subject for emphasis, which in later Greek
became routine even with non-emphatic subjects. Verb-final sentences
thus are mostly found when the object is also extracted to the left for
emphatic purposes <span class="citation" data-cites="horrocks2007">(Horrocks 2007, 623)</span>.</p>
<p>Using the treebanked corpora, we can observe a noticeable difference
between the patterns attested in the literary texts and those from
documentary texts. While in the literary treebanked corpus, verb-final
patterns are much more prevalent (more than 2/3 of results), in the
papyri, both from PapyGreek’s corpus and from the automatically
annotated <a href="https://github.com/alekkeersmaekers/duke-nlp/tree/master/xml">Duke-nlp
corpus</a>, the ratio is inverted, with verb-final patterns being much
less frequent.</p>
