<p>Things left to incorporate:</p>
<ul>
<li><span class="citation" data-cites="celano2014">Celano
(2014a)</span>: Greek topic and focus structures are more complicated
than what Dik suggested</li>
<li><span class="citation" data-cites="holton2019">Holton et al.
(2019)</span>: Topic and focus can be defined in a variety of ways:
referring to prosodic, pragmatic, semantic and/or syntactic factors, and
in Medieval and Early Modern Greek, only prosodic properties could
determine topical/focal elements, but these are not accessible to us
anymore; the same applies to Greek in the papyri, naturally.</li>
<li>New Testament: <span class="citation" data-cites="pitts2022">Pitts
(2022)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="kwong2005">Kwong
(2005)</span></li>
